SIMPLE: swain
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Swain
<hw>Swain</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE. <ets>swain</ets>,
<ets>swein</ets>, Icel. <ets>sveinn</ets> a boy, servant; akin to Sw.
<ets>sven</ets>, Dan. <ets>svend</ets>, AS. <ets>sw⟦amac⟧n</ets>, OHG.
<ets>swein</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A servant.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Him behoves serve himself that has no <qex>swain</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Chaucer.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A young man dwelling in the country; a rustic; esp.,
a cuntry gallant or lover; -- chiefly in poetry.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>It were a happy life⟦br⟧
To be no better than a homely <qex>swain</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Blest <qex>swains</qex>! whose nymphs in every grace excel.</q>
<rj><qau>Pope.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Swainish</ent>⟦br⟧
